export const theHusbandsSecret = {
    id: 'thly1221',
    title: 'The Husband\'s Secret',
    author: 'Liane Moriarty',
    readIn: 'December 2021',
    imageloc: require('../images/theHusbandsSecret.jpg'),
    length: '13h, 44min',
    year: 2021,
    month: 12,
    audiobook: true,
    physicalbook: false,
    review: 'Wow, what a book! This is my second book by Liane Moriarty, and it did not disappoint. \'The Husband\'s Secret\' is a hilarious, mysterious and thought-provoking novel about how well we know our spouses - and, ultimately, ourselves. Let me start with the sentences that drew my attention to this book in the first place: "Imagine that your husband wrote you a letter, to be opened after his death. Imagine, too, that the letter contains his deepest, darkest secret - something with the potential to destroy not just the life you built together, but the lives of others as well. Imagine, then, that you stumble across that letter while your husband is still very much alive..." Alluring, isn\'t it? We follow three story lines, which gives the book a fairly slow start, but it grows addictive when you know the characters and their circumstances. You wonder; what is the husband\'s secret? How bad could it possibly be? And how are these three story lines connected? The first and primary story is about Cecilia Fitzpatrick, a devoted wife and mother, and a pillar of her small community. Her life is seemingly orderly and spotless, until she finds a letter hidden in a shoe box in the attic. Next story line is about Tess, who flees to Sydney with her son when she finds out that her husband has fallen in love with her best friend (who also happens to be her cousin). Then there is Rachel, an older women, still struggling with grief and rage after her daughter was found murdered in a park a few decades ago. Without spoiling anything, I must say that the \'secret\' isn\'t really a mystery or particularly exciting, and its reveal is a bit anti-climatic. What floats this book is the characters and Liane Moriarty\'s excellent writing style. The dialogue and dynamics between the characters are funny and entertaining, and the author is able to express those rare pieces of human honesty - little thoughts, feelings and behaviors that are personal and strange, yet instantly recognizable. Recommended for everyone who needs an entertaining novel!',
}

